@0    = ~<CHARNAME>, we did it! We managed to defeat this spawn of hell with our combined forces, and I feel as if a great weight has been taken off of my soul. I thank you on behalf of the Order for this heroic deed.~ [c#ablank]
@1    = ~I wish to inform the Order as soon as possible of this fortunate turn of events. Let us travel quickly to Athkatla!~
@2    = ~<CHARNAME>, you've done it! You managed to defeat this spawn of hell! I cannot help but feel as if a great weight has been taken off of my soul. I thank you on behalf of the Order for this heroic deed.~ [c#ablank]
@3    = ~<CHARNAME>, please let us travel to the headquarters of the Order, so that my comrades can learn of this beast's death.~
@4    = ~<CHARNAME>, I trust that you will take your duty to the Order seriously and destroy this dragon, which Firkraag turned out to be. I will aid you with all of my power in this, and I hope that we shall face the creature soon.~ [c#ablank]
@5    = ~Yes, you are right. Let us prepare, and face this dragon in battle.~
@6    = ~I told you from the very start that Firkraag is not my top priority, Ajantis.~
@7    = ~Ajantis, you have my word that we shall destroy this Firkraag. Right now is simply not the proper time. Rest assured that we shall do it as soon as possible, though.~
@8    = ~Ajantis, I'm planning to do so... but not right now!~
@9    = ~You left taking revenge on Firkraag to me, and it's for me alone to decide if I shall face him and when I will do so.~
@10   = ~I'm content with your answer, <CHARNAME>. You should know that this means a lot to me.~
@11   = ~(sigh) I will settle for this answer, <CHARNAME>. You should know that this means a lot to me.~
@12   = ~<CHARNAME>! Garren Windspear's child remains in the clutches of evil. He needs our aid, and the Order looks to you for help!~ [c#ablank]
@13   = ~I already have the key. Just a little longer, and Garren's child will be free.~
@14   = ~We're searching in the right place, Ajantis. Firkraag keeps Garren's child imprisoned here, and we shall free him as soon as we know how.~
@15   = ~You should know me better than to cast doubt on my motives! Of course we will release Garren's son as soon as possible.~
@16   = ~We will release Garren's child at the earliest opportunity.~
@17   = ~I'm absolutely aware of your opinion in this matter. Keep quiet; your constant complaining doesn't help at all.~
@18   = ~This is the only proper answer. Let us set about it instantly!~
@19   = ~You should make sure that it happens soon, <CHARNAME>. Your jauntiness is inappropriate and completely out of place!~
@20   = ~<CHARNAME>, you accepted the offer of this... bandit to run your own thieves guild?! You, the light of my heart, the leader of a pack of thieves?! I don't know what to say!~ [c#ablank]
@21   = ~I feared you would have a bit of a problem with my decision. Can't you look on the bright side of it all? How we might gain from this?~
@22   = ~Then simply keep quiet. How I wish to earn my money is my own affair.~
@23   = ~No, I don't see this bright side you speak of. You, ally with this scum... what about your path of goodness and righteousness? What has become of it, <CHARNAME>? How can you team up with such people without betraying yourself, without betraying... us?!~
@24   = ~It doesn't have to end this way. Open your eyes to the possibilities this might offer! What makes you believe I will sink to the same level as murderers and criminals?~
@25   = ~Ajantis, my decision is final. I will use the guild as a way to effect the proceedings of this town, not for my own personal benefit. You do the same thing, the only difference is that you do so by means of your Order, and I shall do so from the shady side streets. It's not as bad as you think!~
@26   = ~You, you, you, always only you and your Order! My decision is made, and if it doesn't suit your plans, I cannot help you!~
@27   = ~You truly think so? You're obliged to a paladin of Helm, <CHARNAME>. What applies to me has to apply to you as well, otherwise our attachment is invalid!~
@28   = ~Ajantis, no! Please, I don't want us to come apart this way.~
@29   = ~Then it must be invalid. I don't know what to say, but you may leave if you wish. You will only hinder me if you are going to be like this.~
@30   = ~Ajantis, no! Please, it just can't be that we come apart like this. We pledged our troth - until the end of all times!~
@31   = ~Because you will be working with murderers and criminals, and you want to be the leader. <CHARNAME>, this is another turn of the screw! You're obliged to a paladin of Helm, <CHARNAME>. What applies to me has to apply to you as well, otherwise our attachment is invalid!~
@32   = ~There's great naivety in your words. Do you think you could last in the world of crime? I wish you had declined that offer, but it's too late now. <CHARNAME>, you're obliged to a paladin of Helm. What applies to me has to apply to you as well, otherwise our attachment is invalid!~
@33   = ~Ajantis, no! Please, we must not come apart this way.~
@34   = ~I wish it was different, but your decision is definitive. You have chosen the dark side... (groan) I have no option but to keep an eye on your dealings as a guild leader on behalf of the Order.~
@35   = ~Our engagement is broken herewith.~
@36   = ~I assumed that much. I know your principles well enough to know that it was your last word on the subject.~
@37   = ~Ajantis, please, I... Is there no other way?~
@38   = ~Your blockheadedness knows no limits! It's just unbelievable. Leave, for all I care, you're just hindering me.~
@39   = ~But this... this is impossible. No, it mustn't be! I've sworn fidelity to you, beloved! We tied the knot. What... what shall we do now?~
@40   = ~Ajantis, I've been stupid... but I'm not base. Please help me emerge from this situation!~
@41   = ~Oh, well, I don't care a copper. I suppose you may leave if you wish. You will only hinder me if you are going to be like this.~
@42   = ~So... So shall it be, then. I will return to the Order to collect myself...~
@43   = ~So shall it be then. <CHARNAME>, nothing more keeps me in this group now. Excuse me. I will return to the Order to collect myself.~
@44   = ~<CHARNAME>, I am supposed to support you in what you do, and I would be willing to do so... As a comrade-in-arms, if you still need me.~
@45   = ~Would you? Yes, then stay with us as a mere traveling companion.~
@46   = ~Ha. You rambled about my 'treading the dark path' only a moment ago, and now you're offering your service as a paladin?~
@47   = ~No, I won't put up with that. Leave: you're just hindering me.~
@48   = ~So shall it be then. I shall continue to support you as long as your deeds are consistent with my duties. You should know, however, that I will keep a close watch on your Shadow Thieves activities.~
@49   = ~I shall continue to support you as long as your deeds are consistent with my duties.~
@50   = ~So shall it be then. You should know, however, that I will keep a close watch on your Shadow Thieves activities.~
@51   = ~I... I cannot see one, beloved. You have made your decision.~
@52   = ~Ajantis, I've been stupid... but I'm not base. Please help me emerge from this situation!~
@53   = ~That... that means that we can't stay together anymore, <CHARNAME>. I don't have a choice. To continue on with you as my wife would mean to betray my duties as a knight. Our union is concluded for a lifetime, <CHARNAME>... I shall leave and pray for mercy, so that Helm may forgive me. Fare... Farewell.~
@54   = ~I can't, <CHARNAME>. What do you expect of me?~
@55   = ~Your blockheadedness knows no limits! This is just unbelievable. Leave, for all I care. You're just hindering me if you are going to be like this.~
@56   = ~<CHARNAME>, I see the amulet of the priestess of Talos in our baggage. I will not tolerate this thievery! Even if Talos's tenets are more than damnable, shall we commit this wicked deed simply to get in the good graces of thieves?! I assume you will return it.~ [c#ablank]
@57   = ~What do you suggest we should do instead of stealing this amulet?~
@58   = ~Ajantis, how shall I earn Mae'Var's trust then?~
@59   = ~I intend to complete this task, and I won't put up with your constant interference with my affairs.~
@60   = ~There must be another, less larcenous, way. The proof we need for the Shadow Thieves can be found somewhere in Mae'Var's guild house, I am sure of it. Let us search for it without playing handymen for these villainous people!~
@61   = ~Hm. You're right. Why am I bullied around by this scum? I shall do as you say, Ajantis.~
@62   = ~Do you really suggest we should rouse the whole thieves' nest and most likely kill them all in the process?! We might procure the proof, but I doubt that Renal will bubble over with joy. He insinuated that we should act discreetly.~
@63   = ~This course of action spells a fight, and whether we would find the proof or not is doubtful. No, I will commit the theft Mae'Var demanded.~
@64   = ~I am relieved to hear that. I could not support conduct such as that. Then let us return the amulet.~
@65   = ~I do not care about what this criminal might think! You've been desperate to work for Renal, and I am grateful for the insight into the Shadow Thieves guild. But I will not wend a spurious way, and I expect the same of you!~
@66   = ~What do you suggest we shall do instead of stealing this amulet?~
@67   = ~You think we should demand the proof straight from the horse's mouth? Perhaps you're right. Why am I bullied around by this scum? I shall do as you say, Ajantis.~
@68   = ~Ajantis, I intend to complete this task, and I won't put up with you constantly interfering with my affairs.~
@69   = ~Then I cannot continue to support your actions. I won't bring you to account here and now, for I still have some respect for you. You will find me in the Order's headquarters should you need me again.~
@70   = ~I hear your words with disbelief, beloved. Can't you see that this is wrong? Are you sure of it? Then... then I can't go on supporting you.~
@71   = ~No, Ajantis, I don't want you to leave. That would mean the end of our engagement, wouldn't it? I shall do as you say and won't commit that theft.~
@72   = ~No, Ajantis, I don't want you to leave. We are married, after all! I shall do as you say and won't commit that theft.~
@73   = ~So shall it be, then. Leave. You're just hindering anyway.~
@74   = ~You would betray the bond between us for the sake of these criminals?! My love, what happened to you?~
@75   = ~Ajantis, no! Of course I wouldn't. I shall do as you say and won't commit the theft.~
@76   = ~I just changed, Ajantis. Leave. Your constant sermons are hindering.~
@77   = ~<CHARNAME>, we shall steal from the temple of Lathander... simply to get into the good graces of a group of thieves?! Explain yourself, for I cannot believe what has become of you.~ [c#ablank]
@78   = ~What do you mean?~
@79   = ~Ajantis, I am not keen on this myself, but we need Mae'Var's trust to procure the proof of his treachery. I want to use every opportunity to raise the gold we need for Imoen's rescue.~
@80   = ~I do this to find Irenicus, who tortured me and killed my friends. The Shadow Thieves have proven friendly so far, and I don't want to let them down. The temple of Lathander will get over the thievery.~
@81   = ~'What has become of me'? What is that supposed to mean?~
@82   = ~I haven't forgotten the goal we are trying to achieve, but the end doesn't justify the means, <CHARNAME>.~
@83   = ~But I want to do it, Ajantis.~
@84   = ~Saying so is easy. And what shall I do instead, pray tell?~
@85   = ~Hm. There might be a chance indeed. I shall do as you say, Ajantis.~
@86   = ~This course of action spells a fight, and whether we'd find the proof is doubtful. No, I will commit the theft Mae'Var demanded.~
@87   = ~I'm relieved to hear that. I couldn't support any other conduct.~
@88   = ~I'm glad to have your support furthermore, even if our path takes a turn you didn't exactly imagine.~
@89   = ~Yes, let us go.~
@90   = ~Fine. But what is 'what has become of me' supposed to mean?~
@91   = ~(sigh) My heart will break if the light of goodness and righteousness does not shine on you again soon, like it did in those days on the Sword Coast. I am afraid that due to my duties as a paladin, I cannot put up with our actions much longer, beloved!~
@92   = ~Then... then I cannot go along with you on this path any longer, my love.~
@93   = ~No, Ajantis, I don't want you to leave. We are married, after all! I shall do as you say and won't commit the theft.~
@94   = ~So... So shall it be then. Herewith our engagement is broken. I will return to the Order to collect myself...~
@95   = ~I may rejoin your party if I begin hearing news of your good deeds again. You were a maintainer of righteousness once... and I owe you my life... Farewell.~
@96   = ~You have been the light of my heart, and I owe you my life... Farewell.~
@97   = ~Your actions cast a slur on you, beloved. I expect you to change this as soon as possible.~
@98   = ~I'm not happy about it myself, Ajantis. But what exactly is your problem with Mae'Var's task?~
@99   = ~Oh, you are constantly whining... It seems like the only times we talk lately are when you preach at me.~
@100  = ~I have no other choice, <CHARNAME>. I'm a paladin and therefore bound by honor!~
@101  = ~(sigh) I know. I'm not happy about how things are working out, either. What's your suggestion regarding Mae'Var's errand?~
@102  = ~I'm tired of hearing this. Getting involved with you was a mistake. Leave, you're just hindering me as it is.~
@103  = ~What are you doing, my love?! You promised not to steal from the temple of Lathander, but now I see their statuette in our baggage. Well, I hope you just wanted to 'take a peek' at it. Do not try to leave the temple along with it. I won't tolerate this theft!~ [c#ablank]
@104  = ~What are you doing, <CHARNAME>? Do not tell me you are about to steal from the temple? I see their statuette in our baggage. Well, I hope you just wanted to 'take a peek' at it. Do not try to leave the temple along with it. I won't tolerate this theft!~ [c#ablank]
@105  = ~Beloved, you promised not to fulfill Mae'Var's infamous request, but now I catch you accomplishing the very same thing!~ [c#ablank]
@106  = ~Oh, my! I knew I had forgotten something. I didn't want to steal from Lathander's temple, Ajantis. I quite honestly forgot to put the statuette back!~
@107  = ~Oh, my! I knew I had forgotten something. I didn't want to steal from Talos' temple, Ajantis. I quite honestly forgot to put the amulet back!~
@108  = ~Well, I've changed my mind, Ajantis. I'll be doing as Mae'Var asks.~
@109  = ~What do you care?! Why must I vindicate myself all the time?!~
@110  = ~Well, I've changed my mind, Ajantis. I'll be doing as Mae'Var asks. I don't care about your opinion.~
@111  = ~What have you done, my love?! You wish to follow Mae'Var's nefarious request, to make yourself a thug's handmaid?!~ [c#ablank]
@112  = ~Well, I do what seems right to me, Ajantis.  I will work for Mae'Var.~
@113  = ~<CHARNAME>, I expected that you wouldn't follow Mae'Var's nefarious request, but now I catch you accomplishing the very same thing! I cannot continue to support your actions. I won't bring you to account here and now, for I still have some respect for you, but I will return to the Order.~ [c#ablank]
@114  = ~You made common cause with this blackguard, and you lied to me. There's just one way to respond to this, <CHARNAME>. Our engagement is broken herewith. I will return to the Order to collect myself...~
@115  = ~I'm a paladin of Helm, beloved! Whatever did you think? I expect righteous demeanor from you, just like from myself!~
@116  = ~You want me to believe this? You... you *are* a maintainer of righteousness, but the loss of your soul weakened you considerably. I believe you, but you have committed a theft, <CHARNAME>. What shall we do?~
@117  = ~Could we not just put it back?~
@118  = ~Well, I've changed my mind, Ajantis. It's good the way it is.~
@119  = ~No, it's not that simple, <CHARNAME>. Stealing is a crime, and you'll have to bear the consequences.~
@120  = ~You made common cause with this blackguard. There's just one way to respond to this, <CHARNAME>.~
@121  = ~You... you wish to break our engagement and abandon me?~
@122  = ~Just leave: you're hindering me, anyway.~
@123  = ~But this... this is impossible. No, it mustn't be! I have sworn fidelity to you, beloved! We tied the knot. What... what shall we do now?~
@124  = ~Ajantis, I didn't mean to! My actions were naive. Please, take it and return it to the temple. Would you do this for me?~
@125  = ~Alas, now it's all the same. I don't know what to say. Leave if you must. You're just hindering me as it is.~
@126  = ~My honor dictates it, <CHARNAME>, if you intend to work for thieves and assassins!~
@127  = ~No, Ajantis, please! I don't want to lose you... not by any means. My actions were naive. Please, take it and return it to the temple. Would you do this for me?~
@128  = ~I see. Then it's about time to break our engagement and go our separate ways.~
@129  = ~Then... then the time has come. Herewith our engagement is broken. I will return to the Order to collect myself...~
@130  = ~I cannot, <CHARNAME>. You've taken it wilfully... My heart is heavy with grief, but there's no other choice.~
@131  = ~<CHARNAME>, shall I work for some common thieves and criminals? We approach their den with stolen goods in our pocket. You're not serious, are you?!~ [c#ablank]
@132  = ~I can't approve of your course of action. I will return to the Order.~
@133  = ~I've told you before that I can't accept this doing. We will not meet again.~
@134  = ~My love, you... you know that I cannot allow this. What shall we do now?~
@135  = ~Please, Ajantis, I fail to see any other option.~
@136  = ~What we should have done long ago. Probably it's best that you leave.~
@137  = ~Another option for what?! Pleasing criminals and murderers? Why are you doing this?~
@138  = ~I want to avoid great bloodshed, Ajantis.~
@139  = ~Because I have reasons to do so, Ajantis. Can't you understand?~
@140  = ~Ajantis, I'm tired of your constant paternalism!~
@141  = ~You sell your soul for these thugs? This thieves' den should be smoked out. I cannot support you in this!~
@142  = ~Well, then it's probably about time to break off our engagement and to part with one another.~
@143  = ~Well, then it's probably about time to break off our relationship and to part with one another.~
@144  = ~What are you doing?! I must defend the Order!~ [c#ablank]
@145  = ~<CHARNAME>, these svirfneblin are not evil. I will not allow you to slaughter them!~ [c#ablank]
@146  = ~<CHARNAME>! What you are doing here is evil! By Helm! My honor dictates that I fight you! Evil must be purged wherever it is found, even among companions!~ [c#ajan29]
@147  = ~<CHARNAME>, I see that you're making decisions I cannot approve of time and again. Be sure to accomplish noble deeds and decide for the good of all in the future, or else I will be impelled to turn against you!~ [c#ablank]
@148  = ~And again you have done something I cannot approve of! I've already warned you. Now it comes to this... draw your weapon and defend yourself!~ [c#ablank]
@149  = ~I... I can't believe it has to end this way. Just as I believed you to be mine again!~
@150  = ~<CHARNAME>, I already know you from our times on the Sword Coast, but your reputation here in these parts is none too good. I trust this will take a turn for the better soon. Let's proceed together on the path of righteousness!~ [c#ablank]
@151  = ~<CHARNAME>, your reputation here in these parts is none too good. I trust this will take a turn for the better soon. Let's proceed together on the path of righteousness!~ [c#ablank]
@152  = ~<CHARNAME>, I'm dissatisfied with how you are leading this group. Our deeds do not speak of goodness and righteousness! We must help the people we encounter.~ [c#ablank]
@153  = ~<CHARNAME>, let our deeds shine in the light of good and righteousness. I am not satisfied with how you are leading this group.~ [c#ablank]
@154  = ~<CHARNAME>, our deeds don't speak the tongue of goodness and righteousness! We must help the people we encounter. Only thus shall we rise in estimation.~ [c#ablank]
@155  = ~By Helm! I cannot follow you on this path any longer! I can bear no more. Raise your weapon and defend yourself.~ [c#ajan31]
@156  = ~By Helm! I cannot follow you on this path any longer! Your deeds are evil! I... I've failed, beloved. Draw your weapon and defend yourself!~ [c#ajan31]
@157  = ~<CHARNAME>, I'm not happy about how this group is turning out. Our actions are casting a dark shadow upon us, while we should spread the light of honesty instead. We cannot go on like this! I will not stand by while this party descends into depravity.~ [c#ajan06]
@158  = ~Ajantis, I'm not happy either. Trust me though, our actions will shine in a better light again soon.~
@159  = ~Ajantis, I have a mission to complete, and that's exactly what I am doing, namely the best I can.~
@160  = ~Ahhhh, what's that supposed to mean? Not everyone can shine with honesty. Our deeds provide the means to achieve our goals, no more, no less.~
@161  = ~It relieves me to hear this, <CHARNAME>. With an expectation of an improvement, I will continue to follow you, even if the current situation is barely agreeable with my duties as a knight.~
@162  = ~It relieves me to hear it, my love. I can't believe that I have thought so wrong of you. Let us move on and please Helm with our future actions. The current situation is barely consistent with my duties as a knight.~
@163  = ~As 'best' as you can, <CHARNAME>? I'm beginning to doubt it. There's something evil about your actions, and that doesn't go well with my duties as a knight. I shall keep on following you, but we must resume the proper path.~
@164  = ~As 'best' as you can, <CHARNAME>? I... I'm beginning to doubt it. Don't misunderstand me, my love, but there's an evil touch about your actions. I can't reconcile this with my duties as a knight anymore. Let's resume the proper path quickly!~
@165  = ~If that's as it is, I'm beginning to doubt that your goals are the same as mine, <CHARNAME>. There's something evil about your actions, and that doesn't go well with my duties as a knight. I shall keep on following you, but we must resume the proper path.~
@166  = ~What a tone you are speaking to me in! I can't believe you've fooled me like this. I... I'm beginning to doubt, my love. There's something evil about your actions, and that doesn't go well with my duties as a knight. Let us move on and please Helm with our future actions! Please, show me you're still the person I thought you to be.~
@167  = ~<CHARNAME>, this deed was a noble one! I see we're headed in the right direction now. Let us proceed in this sense!~ [c#ablank]
@168  = ~<CHARNAME>, I am deeply contented with our deeds. We follow the righteous path, the path of Helm. I thank Helm most sincerely for we are fighting together again. Let us keep it up!~ [c#ajan04]
@169  = ~<CHARNAME>, your deeds reflect your true colors of righteousness. I'm delighted with our course! Let us proceed as bravely furthermore!~ [c#ablank]
@170  = ~With the decision you made to solve this trial, you chose the dark side, <CHARNAME>, for it was evil.~
@171  = ~Well, I'm not really surprised. So let us face this monstrosity Irenicus. But I will keep an eye on you, as I have done before.~
@172  = ~I watch your change of heart with great interest, <CHARNAME>. It seems that your dark side gains the mastery. So let us face this monstrous Irenicus. But I will keep an eye on you, as I have done before.~
@173  = ~<CHARNAME>, you turned! You turned to the dark!~ [c#ablank]
@174  = ~Now, of all times - so close to your reunition with your soul, the evil takes you over!~
@175  = ~You, the light of my heart, lost to the evil...~
@176  = ~I... I know it is the loss of your soul. It has to be! But it happened...~
@177  = ~<CHARNAME>, I cannot be the betrothed of an evil woman... Helm forgive me, but I have to break my vow!~
@178  = ~I am delighted to see you tread the path of light, <CHARNAME>! You have solved all the imposed trials in a truly virtuous way.~ [c#ablank]
@179  = ~I watch your change of heart with great interest. Could you take a turn for the better after all? This deed raises my hopes. Now I wish to join you in this final battle ahead all the more!~
@180  = ~I did expect no less from you, but it's pleasant to watch you tread the path of righteousness without hesitation.~
@181  = ~Let us rout Irenicus, for he's a monster. You have displayed true grandness, however.~
@182  = ~Let us rout Irenicus, for he's a monster. You, however, have displayed true grandness, my love.~
@183  = ~Now we are under an illusionary spell of a mighty wyrm once more, our shapes transformed...~ [c#ablank]
@184  = ~I'm aware of the difference, and I haven't forgotten our obligation to the good Lady Silver. But still, unpleasant memories suggest themselves, memories of the red wyrm's powerful magic, which fooled us in the Windspear Hills.~
@185  = ~The magic of dragons is powerful indeed, and mortals that we are should be glad if they're well-disposed towards us.~
@186  = ~Uh, you're right. This memory is quite unpleasant, so let's hurry. Then we'll be out of this more quickly.~
@187  = ~As you said already, the situation is completely different.~
@188  = ~Then let's not talk about it further.~
@189  = ~Indeed. Now then, let's conclude this task and leave this creepy place.~
@190  = ~As you wish. Let's conclude this task and leave this creepy place.~
@191  = ~My suggestion is all the same. Let's go about our task and leave this creepy place.~
@192  = ~What was the point of this cruel game, <CHARNAME>?! To pretend you want to sacrifice those desperate people to the Spider Queen... Are you completely out of your mind?!~ [c#ablank]
@193  = ~I know it might sound questionable now, but I just wanted to see how far I could go.~
@194  = ~(sigh) Fortunately, you were there to set it right.~
@195  = ~(sigh) Fortunately, you were there to set it right.~
@196  = ~I had a good reason to do so. What's the problem?~
@197  = ~I wonder which of us is truly out of their mind. You disobey all too often, paladin, and this was the last time!~
@198  = ~Really? Well, your former deeds put a favorable complexion on you, so there's still hope for you. I will keep an eye on you, however, <CHARNAME>, and I will not hesitate to bring you to account for any evil actions.~
@199  = ~That's stretching it too far! Your doings were villainous! I call you to account here and now. Draw your weapon and defend yourself! For the glory of Helm!~ [c#ajan03]
@200  = ~You don't say! I am honor-bound as a paladin. Those doings were villainous! Your evil ways end here. Draw steel, and we will settle this dispute once and for all!~ [c#ajan07]
@201  = ~Save your mockery! As a paladin, I am honor-bound, something alien to your nature, it seems. Those doings were villainous! Your evil ways end here. Draw steel and we will settle this dispute once and for all!~ [c#ajan07]
@202  = ~I don't believe a word of it! As a paladin, I am honor-bound, something alien to your nature, it seems. Those doings were villainous! Your evil ways end here. Draw steel, and we will settle this dispute once and for all!~ [c#ajan07]
@203  = ~Are you mocking me? Well, your former deeds put a favorable complexion on you, so there's still hope for you. I will keep an eye on you, however, <CHARNAME>, and I will not hesitate to bring you to account for any evil actions.~
@204  = ~Especially... especially from you of whom I had never expected such a thing! Explain yourself, my love!~
@205  = ~I'm against it myself. I will never do something like that again.~
@206  = ~Ajantis, I wanted it exactly this way. Why are you always interfering in my business?!~
@207  = ~That's stretching it too far! You had the chance to change your mind and to rescue those people, but you wanted to send them to the temple willingly instead!~
