@435  = ~Oh, I don't know about that. The attention is nice, and he doesn't seem to mind.~
@436  = ~Sir Ajantis, you go too far. This is really none of your concern.~
@437  = ~He is a good man, but faces many trials. He relies heavily on your judgement, my lady. With your guidance, he might rise above his troubles. Please use whatever discretion is at your disposal to keep him on the path of Helm. He will thank you for it, my lady.~
@438  = ~I shall keep that in mind. Thank you for your opinion.~
@439  = ~Anomen is old enough to make his own decisions. I will not tell him what to do.~
@440  = ~I am still undecided about how far I want this relationship to go. I need to think about it some more.~
@441  = ~Sir Ajantis, please do not interfere in our relationship.~
@442  = ~I would never advise to enter a commitment before you are prepared to do so, my lady. But I would encourage you to give it some thought. No doubt Anomen thinks of little else.~
@443  = ~I will think on it. Thank you for your concern.~
@444  = ~Are you this nosey with everyone?~
@445  = ~Sir Ajantis, do not trouble yourself. We'll work it out when we're ready.~
@446  = ~It was not my intention to interfere in your personal life, my lady. I am sorry if I have offended you.~
@447  = ~I am sure you know best, my lady. I shall leave the situation to your mercy and your discretion.~
@448  = ~My lady, that would be cruel. I shall leave the matter to your mercy and your discretion, but I urge you to reconsider.~
@449  = ~Then I shall leave the matter in your capable hands. I trust your wisdom and discretion.~
@450  = ~I apologize. It was not my intention to pry. I merely wished the best possible outcome for both of you. I shall say no more on the matter.~
@451  = ~<CHARNAME>, would you step aside a moment?~ [c#ablank]
@452  = ~That was a difficult decision Anomen had to make. I thank you for the strength and support you gave him when he needed it most. It remains to be seen how this decision will affect him, but I hope, in time, that he may take some comfort in the fact that his lawful behavior is pleasing to Helm, if not to his father.~
@453  = ~Indeed, Anomen's choice was not easy, but I am glad he was able to find strength in his convictions.~
@454  = ~He could hardly let that old sot walk all over him, could he?~
@455  = ~It doesn't really matter.~
@456  = ~As am I.~
@457  = ~I would hope Anomen was driven by more than defiance, as well as you, <CHARNAME>.~
@458  = ~Do you think so? It does, to him.~
@459  = ~That was a difficult decision Anomen had to make. I am somewhat... disappointed by the sort of encouragement you gave him. I hope he will not regret his action.~
@460  = ~That was his dead sister in that urn!~
@461  = ~He will do what he thinks is right.~
@462  = ~Revenge will not return his sister to life, and he has made a vow. He must live with the consequences.~
@463  = ~He has made a vow. He must live with the consequences.~
@464  = ~It does, to him!~
@465  = ~<CHARNAME>, may I have a word with you apart from the others?~ [c#ablank]
@466  = ~Sir Anomen has been tested and found worthy, and I am happy for him. He certainly deserves the honor bestowed upon him. But surely, he owes some of his success to the good advice he received.~
@467  = ~If you are referring to the advice I gave him, I thank you, but I would like to think he would have reached that decision on his own.~
@468  = ~If you are referring to the advice I gave him, I thank you, but all I did was give him a nudge down the path I thought would make him happier in the end.~
@469  = ~Well, thank you. I did what I thought best.~
@470  = ~Yes, he does flounder about if you don't walk him through everything, doesn't he?~
@471  = ~I should like to think so, but... well, please allow me to congratulate you for having such a positive influence. I have no doubt that Anomen will look back on his trials and be content that he made the right choice. Nor will he forget whose words gave him the encouragement he needed.~
@472  = ~Sometimes, we all need a bit of help. Please allow me to congratulate you for having such a positive influence. I have no doubt that Anomen will look back on his trials and be content that he made the right choice. Nor will he forget whose words gave him the encouragement he needed.~
@473  = ~Then, please allow me to congratulate you for having such a positive influence. I have no doubt that Anomen will look back on his trials and be content that he made the right choice. Nor will he forget whose words gave him the encouragement he needed.~
@474  = ~I think that this success will give him a bit more confidence, even if he needed help at the time.~
@475  = ~<CHARNAME>, may I have a word with you apart from the others?~ [c#ablank]
@476  = ~Sir Anomen has been tested and found worthy, and I am happy for him. He certainly deserves the honor bestowed upon him. But surely, love, he owes some of his success to your good advice.~
@477  = ~Thank you, Ajantis, but I would like to think he would have reached that decision on his own.~
@478  = ~Thank you, Ajantis, but all I did was give him a nudge down the path I thought would make him happier in the end.~
@479  = ~Thank you. I did what I thought best.~
@480  = ~I should like to think so, but... well, let us say that your advice was timely and wise. I have no doubt that Sir Anomen will look back on his trials and be content that he made the right choice. Nor will he forget whose words gave him the encouragement he needed.~
@481  = ~Yes, my love, sometimes, we all need a bit of help. Still, your guidance was both wise and timely. I have no doubt that Sir Anomen will look back on his trials and be content that he made the right choice. Nor will he forget whose words gave him the encouragement he needed.~
@482  = ~And it has worked out for the best for everyone involved, my love. I have no doubt that Sir Anomen will look back on his trials and be content that he made the right choice. Nor will he forget whose words gave him the encouragement he needed.~
@483  = ~Anomen has been tested and found wanting, <CHARNAME>, and I am saddened by this result. He certainly did not make the best decision. But surely, he did not reach this decision in the absence of any advice.~
@484  = ~If you are referring to the advice I gave him, he would have reached that decision with or without my advice.~
@485  = ~If you are referring to the advice I gave him, all I did was give him a nudge down the path I thought would bring him the most satisfaction.~
@486  = ~I did what I thought best.~
@487  = ~Mind your own business, paladin!~
@488  = ~(sigh) Perhaps, but what is done, is done, and Anomen must be held responsible for his own decisions. I cannot change the past, but I must inform you that it is my duty as a paladin to maintain vigilance. I had hoped that you would exert what influence you might have... differently. I will watch your decisions very carefully.~
@489  = ~Although I cannot agree with his decisions, Anomen must be held responsible for them. I only hope that such satisfaction as he receives will compensate him for his loss.~
@490  = ~I cannot change the past, but I must inform you that it is my duty as a paladin to maintain vigilance. I had hoped that you would exert what influence you might have... differently. I will watch your decisions very carefully.~
@491  = ~I shall mind my own business, even as Anomen must live with the consequences of his decision. And it is my duty as a paladin to maintain vigilance. I had hoped that you would exert what influence you might have... differently. I will watch your decisions very carefully.~
@492  = ~My love, may I have a word with you apart from the others?~ [c#ablank]
@493  = ~Anomen has been tested and found wanting, Lady <CHARNAME>, and I am saddened by this result. He certainly did not make the best decision. But surely, he did not reach this decision in the absence of any advice.~
@494  = ~(sigh) Perhaps, but what is done, is done, and Anomen must be held responsible for his own decisions. My love, I am honestly amazed that you offered him the advice you did.~
@495  = ~Honestly, <CHARNAME>, I am amazed by what you 'thought best'. Ultimately, of course, Anomen must live with the consequences of his own decisions, but he did not make them alone. After all we've been through, and all we've shared, I had not thought you would encourage such lawlessness.~
@496  = ~I had hoped that you would exert whatever influence you might have... differently. It saddens me, my love, but I must watch your decisions very carefully.~
@497  = ~I shall mind my own business, even as Anomen must live with the consequences of his decision. And it is my duty as a paladin to maintain vigilance. I had hoped that you would exert whatever influence you might have... differently. It saddens me, my love, but I must watch your decisions very carefully.~
@498  = ~I cannot change the past, but I must inform you that it is my duty as a paladin to maintain vigilance. I had hoped that you would exert whatever influence you might have... differently. It saddens me, but I must watch your decisions very carefully.~
@499  = ~I learned you were expelled from the Most Holy Order of the Radiant Heart! <CHARNAME>, this is great shame you put on yourself. Under these circumstances, I am incapable of accompanying you further. I will seek a place where I will be able to fulfill my duty better. Farewell.~ [c#ablank]
@500  = ~It is a harsh truth that you were expelled from the Most Holy Order of the Radiant Heart! <CHARNAME>, this is great shame you put on yourself. Under these circumstances, I am incapable of accompanying you further. I will seek a place where I will be able to fulfill my duty better. Farewell.~ [c#ablank]
@501  = ~<CHARNAME>, you failed as a priestess of Helm, and the church has abandoned you! How could you let this happen?~ [c#ablank]
@502  = ~I helped and gave advice as well as I could, Ajantis!~
@503  = ~I waited for you to comment on that.~
@504  = ~Actually I am quite happy to be rid of them.~
@505  = ~Whatever your motivation was, as a paladin of Helm, I cannot be your betrothed any longer!~
@506  = ~That... that means we cannot stay together any longer. We made a vow... <CHARNAME>, I will... go and seek forgetting in fighting missions of the Order. Fare... farewell.~
@507  = ~Whatever your reason was, I am a paladin of Helm. I cannot follow you any longer. Farewell.~
@508  = ~<CHARNAME>, it is a great pity we didn't keep my family shield. I can only hope you have a sincere reason for its absence.~ [c#ablank]
@509  = ~If this shield means a lot to you, we will get it back as soon as possible.~
@510  = ~It is at a safe place now, and you have better armor.~
@511  = ~Oh, dear. Please stop this whining. I'm sure your wealthy family won't even notice it's gone.~
@512  = ~That was an unfriendly remark, <CHARNAME>.~
@513  = ~I do not insist on using it, since it might not provide the best protection against the enemies we face, but it is still an item of great value to me... And it belongs to my family, truth be told.~
@514  = ~My family shield! There it is. <CHARNAME>, it is good we have it back.~ [c#ablank]
@515  = ~Stop this insane questioning! You are twisting <PRO_HISHER> words!~
@516  = ~No more interruptions! Is it too much to ask for <PRO_HIMHER> to answer a question about <PRO_HISHER> favorite color?!~
@517  = ~Imprison Lady <CHARNAME>?! I will never allow such a thing!~
@518  = ~Of course we will face this evil being! It is a matter of honor!~
@519  = ~We *will* return, foul beast! Your fate is sealed!~
@520  = ~In Helm's name, <CHARNAME>! I hear your words with horror! We are here to demand justice for the Order and for Lord Garren Windspear!~
@521  = ~<CHARNAME>! This is evil! I will not take your betrayal of Lord Windspear lying down. Defend yourself!~
@522  = ~<CHARNAME>! This is evil! I'll not take your betrayal of Lord Windspear lying down. Defend yourself!~
@523  = ~<CHARNAME>! This is evil! I will not take your betrayal of Lord Windspear lying down. I... I have to fight you. Defend yourself!~
@524  = ~I wouldn't have remained silent to this deception either, Sir Keldorn. <CHARNAME>, this is against my principles.~
@525  = ~Sir Sarles, I assure you that <CHARNAME> had good reasons to believe this material would fulfill your demand.~
@526  = ~Wait! Whom do I see! Sir Ajantis, my former squire and now an honored knight himself. I greet you! Seeing you in this group should allay my suspicion.~
@527  = ~Sir Keldorn, my former mentor and highest esteemed knight of the Order! I am happy to see you.~
@528  = ~I am also happy about this unexpected reunion. But duty demands that we don't forget the reasons for our being here. I have to ask for your answer!~
@529  = ~Sir Keldorn, my former teacher and good comrade! I am shocked to see you so distressed! What happened?~
@530  = ~My friend, you see me more desperate than I have ever been. Please, <CHARNAME>, stand by my side and help me!~
@531  = ~<CHARNAME>, do you really want to offer Sir Sarles inferior material? It didn't sound as if he would be satisfied with that.~
@532  = ~This... this is utmost joyful! I hadn't expected this happy ending. So defeat turns into victory!~
@533  = ~No, I will not be mute about this lie.~
@534  = ~Sir Sarles, forgive us. What you're holding in your hands is not pure illithium, but an alloy! I can assure you, though, that <CHARNAME> tried to fulfill your demand!~
@535  = ~Sir? Are you listening?~
@536  = ~<CHARNAME>, what horror must I see here! We have to help these people!~
@537  = ~<CHARNAME>, let us free these desperate people soon!~
@538  = ~By Helm, your words are horrifying me, <CHARNAME>! Denying those people aid is most vile! It must be your endeavor to thwart slavery, and I demand accountability from you here and now!~
@539  = ~Anomen, in Helm's name! You don't want to take vengeance for your sister's death in this brutal manner! Remember the tenets of the Order whose knight you are!~
@540  = ~Anomen, in Helm's name! You don't want to take vengeance for your sister's death in this brutal manner! Remember the tenets of the Order whose knight you yearn to become.~
@541  = ~<CHARNAME>, let us help the Order. I'm asking you in behalf of my comrades!~
@542  = ~This... this was the likeness of evil! The avatar of Bhaal! <CHARNAME>, you must be strong! Do not let it overcome you!~
@543  = ~Are you well, <CHARNAME>? You looked in vertigo for a moment.~
@544  = ~This must be gruelling for you. Let us move on and regain your soul!~
@545  = ~He is dead! So that's it? Do you feel different now, <CHARNAME>?~
@546  = ~What a gruesome experience! Where are we? What portrait of evil surrounds us! I fear for you, <CHARNAME>. Let's get closer together and see how we can find our way out of this area soon!~
@547  = ~What a gruesome experience! Where are we? What kind of manifested evil surrounds us! I fear for you, <CHARNAME>. But it has to be, and we will face the evil. Let me fight close at your side!~
@548  = ~You will die, evil creature!~
@549  = ~You will die, evil creature! No more will you trouble my beloved. NO MORE!~
@550  = ~Sir Ajantis, your faithful paladin. Back on the Sword Coast, he fought by your side. But his life is dedicated to Helm and the Most Noble Order of the Radiant Heart. On his Order's behalf, he strives for the good and righteous. Why would he walk down with you?~
@551  = ~Ajantis, it's my personal fight; you don't have to come along.~
@552  = ~You felt Irenicus' power, Ajantis. You don't have to come along.~
@553  = ~Are you determined and prepared for this fight, Ajantis? I must know if I can count on you when we descend these stairs.~
@554  = ~His gaze rests upon you as you turn to him.~
@555  = ~Ajantis, do you...~
@556  = ~Sir Ajantis, your faithful paladin and beloved. By your side, he fights on Helm's behalf for the good. His gaze rests upon you as you turn to him.~
@557  = ~Ajantis... I...~
@558  = ~Let us go below and get this monster of a man! I promised to aid you, and I won't disappoint you!~
@559  = ~No, don't speak, <CHARNAME>. I am there for you as I will be forever more. I'll stand by your side in your fight for your soul. This is also my fight, for I don't want to be - and I cannot be - without you anymore!~
@560  = ~Let us go below and get this monster of a man!~
@561  = ~I had hoped to call you my wife by now. But I understand better than anyone that other things have priority now. When we recover your soul, we shall find the peace we need to tie the knot. Let us go below and get this monster of a man!~
@562  = ~No, do not speak, <CHARNAME>. I will stand by your side in your fight for your soul. I am there for you as I will be forever more... if you want me to. I... (coughs) Let us go down, my lady.~
@563  = ~I do not feel well at the thought of having to work for the Shadow Thieves... but I fear we have to play their games for Imoen's sake. I will help you as long as I can fulfill the tasks with a clear conscience.~
@564  = ~<CHARNAME>, do we really have to collaborate with the Shadow Thieves?~
@565  = ~Well, it seems to be the only way to rescue Imoen right now. But you may rest assured that I won't hesitate to let the light of righteousness shine, should it be necessary.~
@566  = ~I will support this as long as it means gathering information about those criminals. But I will not tolerate breaking the law, <CHARNAME>. Remember this.~
@567  = ~You... you wouldn't take it into consideration, my love? I had banked on the thought that you won't use this part of your training for such purposes!~
@568  = ~Now you became a Shadow Thief, and not only this! The Order will observe your activities, <CHARNAME>. Should it ever come to a confrontation, I cannot fight on your side.~
@569  = ~Maybe you should reconsider whether you want a knight of the Order in your party furthermore, <CHARNAME>.~
@570  = ~You're right, <CHARNAME>. Refuse him bluntly. Let us never fetch and carry for these criminals!~
@571  = ~I cannot approve of this theft! Then we would be on the same level as these thieves. I cannot support you in this. Your... entire behavior doesn't reflect the righteousness I had hoped for. I shall not rejoin you until you appear in a better light. Farewell.~
@572  = ~I cannot approve of this theft! Then we would be on the same level as these thieves. I cannot support you in this. Your deeds don't reflect the righteousness I expect, beloved.~
@573  = ~You can't be serious! <CHARNAME>, I cannot approve of this theft! Then we would be on the same level as these thieves!~
@574  = ~Well, I see, you wish to gain Mae'Var's full confidence. <CHARNAME>, we should check first if we could not speak with this Embarl. What this thieves' chief calls a traitor could turn out to be a refined man, whose life we shouldn't end without good reasons.~
@575  = ~I had hoped you wouldn't kill this man blindly, but rather determine if he renounced his damnable existence as a Shadow Thief. But now, after you have shown him mercy, I'm not sure if it came across properly. Let us hope that he will renounce this occupation forthwith.~
@576  = ~Do not worry about me, knight. Haha, I am gone!~
@577  = ~I will not tolerate us becoming handymen of this evil wizard by any means! <CHARNAME>, I trust we will find out if this Cowled Wizard deserves this first.~
@578  = ~(sighs) Once again, we are playing stooges to this puffed up contemptible person. I advise you not to deploy any two-faced practices in this matter. I can't approve of a theft or the like.~
@579  = ~Why do you accept this arrogant, evil mage into the party, <CHARNAME>?! He shall exercise great care with his utterances, or else this will assuredly lead to strife.~
@580  = ~And here he is again, this pompous would-be knight! (Really, I don't know why I am doing this to myself.)~
@581  = ~<CHARNAME>, this creature is evil... evil to the core. By Helm! We must regard her words with utmost caution.~
@582  = ~No! By Helm, my love, you wouldn't consider an alliance with this dreadful creature?!~
@583  = ~I cannot become a servant of this creature! With this, you are on your own, <CHARNAME>.~
@584  = ~I cannot become a servant of this creature! I thought better of you... With this, you are on your own, <CHARNAME>.~
@585  = ~I cannot become a servant of this creature! <CHARNAME>, I don't have another choice, for what you're doing is evil...~
@586  = ~We shall bring your evil existence to an end, as it is our duty! You don't frighten us! <CHARNAME>, I'm glad you rejected this creature's offer.~
@587  = ~It might well be you who regrets it if we meet again.~
@588  = ~These creatures are evil, <CHARNAME>. Do as you wish if you think you can avoid a bloodshed, but I wouldn't give much on what they offer.~
@589  = ~You're doing *this*? What evil is reflected in you! I cannot support this! We are here to *save* these eggs!~
/*
@590  = ~SPEAK QUICKLY, CHILD OF BHAAL, BEFORE I LOSE MY TEMPER!~
*/
@591  = ~Drizzt Do'Urden treads the path of righteousness. I cannot side with you in this fight, now that you have shown your true colors. By Helm, draw steel and defend yourself!~
@592  = ~<CHARNAME>, Drizzt Do'Urden treads the path of righteousness! I... I fear I have to turn against you. I cannot believe it has to end like this. After I have only just found you again! Draw steel and defend yourself!~
@593  = ~It is obvious your comrades have a better sense of right and wrong. So let's start!~
@594  = ~What a brilliant idea, to seek the support of this strong fighter for righteousness! I'm very pleased, <CHARNAME>.~
@595  = ~This cult reeks of evil, <CHARNAME>. By Helm, let us accept this job!~
@596  = ~Sir Keldorn! My teacher and mentor! I have not seen him for a long time now. He's a good man, <CHARNAME>. Let us hurry and, on behalf of Helm, find this godless cult!~
@597  = ~Please change your mind, <CHARNAME>! This evil must be investigated!~
@598  = ~This is wonderful, <CHARNAME>! You confessed to the true faith. I am glad that I have found a fellow believer in you.~
@599  = ~This is wonderful, <CHARNAME>! Now you have found a true place in the fold of your church.~
@600  = ~I do not understand, <CHARNAME>. Why are you rejecting an offer from the church of your god?~
@601  = ~I don't understand, <CHARNAME>. You rendered the church of Lathander a great service. But why do you accept this offer instead of obtaining one from the church of your own god?~
@602  = ~Sir Keldorn! My teacher and mentor! I have not seen him for a long time now. He is a good man, <CHARNAME>. I'm glad that you want to investigate this godless cult, even if I wish you would do so with assistance of Helm's church.~
@603  = ~Sir Keldorn! My teacher and mentor! I have not seen him for a long time now. He is a good man, <CHARNAME>. I'm glad that you want to investigate this godless cult, even if I don't understand why you don't do so with the blessing of my and your own god!~
@604  = ~Although I am delighted that you want to investigate this godless cult, I wish it wouldn't be on behalf of the evil god of destruction and rebellion. I shall keep an eye on your activities, <CHARNAME>.~
@605  = ~So now you have confessed to the god of evil and destruction. I shall keep an eye on your activities in the future, you can be sure of that.~
@606  = ~What a proud day! Welcome to the Most Holy Order of the Radiant Heart, <CHARNAME>. You took a great step forward to fulfill a great goal in your life.~
@607  = ~I don't understand... You are rejecting a place in the Most Holy Order of the Radiant Heart? <CHARNAME>, I hope you have considered this well, as there will be no second chance.~
@608  = ~This is a great shame you put on the both of us! I am sorry, <CHARNAME>, but I have to go and seek a place where I can fulfill my duty better. Fare well.~
@609  = ~You are turning this ranger in to the Cowled Wizards after all that we've learned about the situation? This is signing his death warrant! I cannot agree to that, <CHARNAME>, and I cannot stay with a group that does. Farewell.~
@610  = ~You are turning this ranger in to the Cowled Wizards after all that we have learned about the situation? I cannot agree to that, <CHARNAME>, it would be signing his death warrant! I will leave you here and now. I can't believe it has to end like this. After I had only just found you again!~
@611  = ~You are turning our comrade in to the Cowled Wizards? This action will sign his death warrant! How could I have been so naive? Now that you have shown your true colors, my honor dictates that I strike against you!~
@612  = ~You are turning our comrade in to the Cowled Wizards? This action will sign his death warrant! I...  I fear I have to turn against you. My honor dictates that I attack! I can't believe it has to end like this. After I had only just now found you again!~
@613  = ~Do not try to threaten us, mage! We are not afraid of your powers! <CHARNAME> won't betray an innocent.~
@614  = ~Well done, <CHARNAME>! I am satisfied you did not betray that ranger.~
@615  = ~And *you* also better not cross my path again, knightling!~
@616  = ~Well done, <CHARNAME>! I am satisfied you did not betray our comrade.~
@617  = ~'Circumstances'! Bah, a treachery is a treachery. What despicable behavior!~
@618  = ~A... geas! Now I understand our discussions better, but it is too late.~
@619  = ~<CHARNAME>, this woman is evil. You are not considering taking her with you? This is the second time you have to make this choice!~
@620  = ~I wasn't talking to you, pompous male!~
@621  = ~Die, malicious man!~
@622  = ~You could not understand!~
@623  = ~What a scorn for life! Don't you dare to put that into action, <CHARNAME>!~
@624  = ~Don't prattle! Those druid brats are not worth the breath. Rather hurry!~
@625  = ~You really did it! What a terrible thing to do! I - I cannot stand for this!~
@626  = ~Wait... the warrior by your side... he bears the insignia of the Order! Who are you? I don't know your face, but I recognize you as a knight of the Order! What are you trying to accomplish here with such tricks?!~
@627  = ~I like to wear this Order's insignia. It... inspires confidence in most people. Don't you do something similar?~
@628  = ~Well, I guess you are right... It was all so long ago.~
@629  = ~(whispers) In the name of Helm, <CHARNAME>! Look at these pitiful people! Is there no way to help them?~
/*
@630  = ~What kind of question is that? Do you want the master of the slave pens to answer?~
*/
@631  = ~That... is a joke, isn't it? By Helm, I thought you wanted to help those people!~
@632  = ~Save the breath for cursing us - <PRO_HESHE> is playing a bad joke on you. Go to the gates; tell them you are delivering a message for Veldrin. Then try to make your way to the surface. Helm's blessing be with you!~
@633  = ~What macabre game are you playing?! I won't tolerate your killing those people for your amusement!~
@634  = ~<CHARNAME>! What... what macabre game are you playing?! I won't tolerate your killing those people for your amusement!~
@635  = ~I had never thought it would end this way. But my honor dictates that I defend the innocent!~
@636  = ~I am glad for those desperate people, <CHARNAME>. Let us wish them well.~
@637  = ~I am glad for those desperate people, <CHARNAME>, although it would have been preferable to provide them with some equipment for their way to the surface.~
@638  = ~You have set them free, <CHARNAME>, but it would have been preferable to clear a way to the surface for them.~
@639  = ~You have set them free, <CHARNAME>, but what odds do you figure for them?~
@640  = ~*Helm's* blessing? ...Who... Well...~
@641  = ~You let him go? <CHARNAME>, he was a murderer!~
@642  = ~...and gone.~
@643  = ~What a pitiful creature! We simply can't walk past this suffering, <CHARNAME>. Please, let us help him!~
@644  = ~Where is Littleman?...~
@645  = ~This can't be much work, <CHARNAME>. I am sure we will find the time to return and help this troubled soul to gain its peace.~
@646  = ~This can't be much work, <CHARNAME>. I am sure we will find the time to return and help this soul to gain its peace.~
@647  = ~Thank you for helping this poor soul, <CHARNAME>.~ [c#ablank]
@648  = ~No, <CHARNAME>! Where's your sense of honor? These beings asked for our help! I cannot support this behavior!~
@649  = ~Save your anger, dear lady; of course we shall free you. I hope you are not injured?~
@650  = ~I see with horror that you're captured here. Save your anger, dear lady; of course we shall free you. I hope you are not injured?~
@651  = ~What macabre game are you playing! I requested that the lady be freed! I will not accompany you any longer.~
@652  = ~<CHARNAME>! What... what macabre game are you playing! I requested that the lady be freed! I will not accompany you any longer.~
@653  = ~I had never thought it would end this way... Fare well!~
@654  = ~This doesn't help much now, Sir... Oh, well. What is now?~
@655  = ~I will not allow that this brave little woman stay in prison! She is not stained by the evil of the shadows, so much is sure.~
@656  = ~You are free to go, brave halfling woman.~
@657  = ~Don't bother about this servant of evil, <CHARNAME>, as his world view is distorted by his wish for revenge and destruction!~
@658  = ~The suffering of these young people hurts my heart, <CHARNAME>. Please change your mind and let us help them. We faced more dangerous things than this skinless creature.~
@659  = ~Excellent, <CHARNAME>! I hoped you would respond this way. Let us aid these young people!~
@660  = ~He... In Helm's name, what a terrible sight! The poor boy. <CHARNAME>, we should do what we can do to stop this murderer!~
@661  = ~What? We are to represent drow, live among them, maybe even work with them?! I do not like this manner of deception.~
@662  = ~Ajantis, your courage is honorable, but to put up a fight against an entire city is far too risky! You know about the dark elves' strength, and they outnumber us by far. Besides, Adalon has just explained her dilemma. Her hands are tied as long as her eggs remain in the drows' possession.~
@663  = ~I don't like the idea either, but that is what we will do.~
@664  = ~Didn't you just say you would follow me into this hell?~
@665  = ~My honor demands that I die in battle rather than walk amongst these evil creatures in such a way!~
@666  = ~You could have spoken up before the Silver Lady. Now it's too late.~
@667  = ~But you are the leader, so lead on.~
@668  = ~I would not question the Silver Lady! And yet...~
@669  = ~The Silver Lady leaves her post? But... I do not...~
@670  = ~That is indeed what I said, and I am not taking back my word.~
@671  = ~I cannot believe this! We are to represent drow, live among them, maybe even work with them? Why all this secrecy? Let's strike against them together! If we act together, we can destroy them!~ [c#ablank]
@672  = ~The Silver Lady will leave her post... I still cannot believe what I have witnessed.~ [c#ablank]
@673  = ~I will follow you into this hell, <CHARNAME>. (sighs) Helm will help me to focus on what is essential, while we walk amongst these fiends. Now may not be the time for justice, but it will come!~
@674  = ~There's a touch of evil on this woman! Can you feel it, too, <CHARNAME>? Who or what are you, woman?~
@675  = ~(laughs) Your questions might be answered later; *perhaps*, much later, little servant of Helm. Simply meet up with my mistress, <CHARNAME>, and you shall see.~
@676  = ~This Rift Device seems to pave our way to the Unseeing Eye. Under these circumstances, I shall help you to retrieve this rod, <CHARNAME>. Should we find it, we must destroy it ere it falls into the hands of this madman. He must use it by no means!~
@677  = ~(whispers) <CHARNAME>! That's ridiculous. Don't get involved with that insanity! What will you answer him?~
@678  = ~You won't use this artifact of destruction! <CHARNAME>, we have to stop him!~
@679  = ~Finally, the time has come to put the end which is due to this 'cult'! Die, ill-fated one!~
@680  = ~Oh, Sir Ajantis. I didn't notice you, Sir. I am glad to see you alive and well.~
@681  = ~Greetings to you, Peony.~
@682  = ~I apologize, but I do not know the person you are travelling with.~
@683  = ~Oh, Sir Ajantis! I am glad to see you alive and well.~
@684  = ~Sir Ajantis! You I recognize. Another member of the Order.~
@685  = ~Greetings to you, Lady Maria. I am sorry we have disturbed you.~
@686  = ~Sir Ajantis, I greet the former squire of my husband.~
@687  = ~Greetings to you, Lady Maria. It is nice to see you again.~
@688  = ~<CHARNAME>, I agree with Anomen. Garren's child needs our help, and the Order is watching you!~
@689  = ~<CHARNAME>, I agree with Anomen. Let us keep on searching; the key to our problem must be somewhere around.~
@690  = ~<CHARNAME>, I agree with Anomen. Garren's child needs our help! Why do we have the key without freeing the child?! Let us turn around!~
@691  = ~<CHARNAME>, I agree with Anomen. Garren's child needs our help! We have the key, so let us release Garren's child!~
@692  = ~<CHARNAME>, we have the required key. Let us release Garren's child!~
@693  = ~Greetings, Lord Windspear. I am desperate to hear about your troubles.~
@694  = ~Greetings, Sir Ajantis. I am glad to see you alive and well.~
@695  = ~Do not worry any longer,  I am sure <CHARNAME> will lead us to the scoundrel's hideout soon, to rescue your child.~
@696  = ~I thank you, and wish you farewell.~
@697  = ~Greetings, Lord Windspear. I am glad we meet without any sorrow burdening you.~ [c#ablank]
@698  = ~Greetings, Sir Ajantis. I can't say how glad I am to see you alive. What happened to you?~
@699  = ~When sent to the Windspear Hills, my comrades and I wanted to approach you. But before we were able to reach your quarters we were captured and held imprisoned by this malicious Firkraag.~
@700  = ~We were on our way to make our presence known to you, but this evil Firkraag got us first. <CHARNAME> came to my comrades' and my aid, as you surely know.~
@701  = ~Greetings, Lord Windspear. I am glad we meet without great sorrow burdening you.~ [c#ablank]
@702  = ~Greetings, Sir Ajantis. We deem it an honor to know a faithful servant of the Watcher in our halls.~ [c#ablank]
@703  = ~I greet thee as well, Guardian Vottnar. Helm looks kindly upon those serving him faithfully.~
@704  = ~What do you mean?~
@705  = ~She has given enough and suffered enough. Now she has to take care of her eggs.~
@706  = ~So what? We have other problems now.~
@707  = ~I cannot understand this behavior. I am taken aback. Never would I have expected a Silver Lady to leave the post she promised to keep.~
@708  = ~A silver dragon is... is the greatest, most majestic creature that I have ever seen. If she is to leave her post... What horrible things must have happened!~
@709  = ~I don't think she promised to guard the exit forever.~
@710  = ~She was ready to sacrifice herself, but not her children. A lot of things seem to change if you have children.~
@711  = ~I know what you think: that a paladin would never give up his task!~
@712  = ~A paladin would not, because if a paladin gave up, he would fail... and fall.~
@713  = ~So you are saying that a paladin who gives up is no paladin? (sigh) Great logic.~
@714  = ~She is not a paladin, but a mother. She volunteered to guard the exit, and now she served enough.~
@715  = ~Ah, just spare me your talking about how good paladins, including yourself, are, Ajantis.~
@716  = ~She said she would guard it, and now she leaves... In the moment of the upcoming war! This is a behavior I would usually call treachery.~
@717  = ~Maybe there is another truth in it... To stop if you aren't capable of fulfilling your duty any more.~
@718  = ~But still, it leaves a bad impression, to go like this... I have to think about this some more.~
@719  = ~I am not talking about myself! I am talking about Lady Adalon.~
@720  = ~I am glad to see you safe, Sir Ajantis. Yes, there was a lot of evil in these hills... I am thankful that you, <PRO_LADYLORD> <CHARNAME>, helped the knights out of there.~
@721  = ~Come here, child... Have you met Eila before? She is my niece from Luskan.~
@722  = ~Eila?! You... you have grown! Last time I saw you, you were a little girl, and now... (cough) Greetings to you, my lady.~
@723  = ~Greetings, Sir Ajantis. I am happy to see you safe and well.~
@724  = ~Thank you for the kind words, my lady. I hope you'll enjoy your stay here with your uncle.~
@725  = ~That I will for sure. It was nice to meet you again.~
@726  = ~It was nice to meet *you* again, my lady.~
@727  = ~It is a great honor the Ever Watchful bestowed on you. You should strive to prove yourself worthy!~
@728  = ~<CHARNAME> is more merciful than you deserve. May Helm show you his justice.~
@729  = ~What great news reached me! Now you are a member of the Most Holy Order of the Radiant Heart as well.~ [c#ablank]
@730  = ~You took a great step forward to fulfill a great goal in your life.~
@731  = ~I am very happy and proud, my love. Let us fight evil together in the name of the Order, side by side!~
@732  = ~This is so... disgusting! Don't you dare to cause another innocent's death by playing this evil game!~
@733  = ~I warned you! I will not tolerate this behavior!~
@734  = ~What a mighty, magnificent sword! I am proud to wield it, <CHARNAME>, and I will make sure with my deeds that I deserve it!~ [c#ablank]
@735  = ~You heard what she said, Ajantis. Guarding the exit became pointless. There is no use in keeping to a promise in this case.~
@736  = ~Her guarding did not become pointless! Imagine how powerful her help in defeating the attacking drow would be. No, she let her allies down.~
@737  = ~No, my... lady, Lady <CHARNAME> is in no need of such 'services'.~
@738  = ~My lady! Are you really up to going into that room with that... I... I... Well, good night. (By Helm!)~
@739  = ~You are not going to pester this lady, are you?!~
@740  = ~Don't you speak with Lady <CHARNAME> in this tone!~
@741  = ~My lady, you are probably not taking this for real! ...Are you?~
@742  = ~This is that horrible creature we met in Baldur's Gate! Now we will bring justice to the murdered children!~
@743  = ~He he, we will see!~
@744  = ~Relax. I am not planning on stealing anything. There has to be another way of receiving the item, we will see.~
@745  = ~In this case you are still trying to earn the trust of a thief, to work for another one. I really don't understand why.~
@746  = ~Well, but knowing you do not mean to steal indeed is good news. So, let us go and see what will come of it.~
@747  = ~Your actions cast a slur on you, beloved. I expect you to change this as soon as possible. Knowing you do not plan on stealing is a great relief, though. Stay on this path of good!~
@748  = ~Or we just don't steal the item. There has to be another way of receiving it, we will see.~

/* ToB part - obviously, this would be for C#aja25j - doh */
@749  = ~Bring me Ajantis, the paladin and knight.~
@750  = ~I cannot do as you ask, Child of Bhaal.  The thread of the one whose name you speak is beyond my sight, as he is sheltered by great powers against an evil summoning. His destiny no longer touches yours.~
@751  = ~You knew the name of the demon this keep holds?! You traitor!~
@752  = ~Such treachery! How could a servant of Helm sink this low?!~
@753  = ~I strongly advise against siding with this demon, <CHARNAME>. Let us confront Odren with these accusations and see what he has to say for himself.~
@754  = ~This man seems very troubled. We should find a way to calm him down!~
@755  = ~Succubi! Tread with care, <CHARNAME>, as these evil creatures do not have good intentions, ever!~
@756  = ~<CHARNAME>! You will not... gamble with this cambion?!~
@757  = ~A... a red dragon! <CHARNAME>, do not be fooled by his civilized air. Remember the tricks and games red dragons like to play! Let us prepare for battle!~
@758  = ~Forced into the service of Helm? A chromatic demon? This doesn't make any sense at all!~
@759  = ~To have to help this... this creature! <CHARNAME>, we should be ready to defeat it, not free it!~
@760  = ~Imps, hell creatures... all this evil, and all in these halls framed with gigantic symbols of Helm's all-seeing eye. This is most disturbing, <CHARNAME>!~
@761  = ~Sarevok! Long-defeated foe from the past. Do we have to face you again? Are you trying to make <CHARNAME>'s life miserable... Again?!~
@762  = ~<CHARNAME>! After everything he put you through on the Sword Coast, after what he did to Gorion, you are not sincerely considering helping him regain his life?~
@763  = ~<CHARNAME>, please reconsider! Remember, the prophecy speaks of a hidden traitor in your midst. What else could he be?~
@764  = ~My lady! You look young and frightened. There must be another way to earn your living?~
@765  = ~My lady! You look young and frightened. There... must be another way to earn your living?~
@766  = ~Tell me about Sir Ajantis.~
@767  = ~Ah, Sir Ajantis. The paladin that has accompanied you since nearly the beginning of your adventures.~
@768  = ~Always fighting for the good and righteous, he set out then to gain honor for his accolade. Now he has reached a level of prowess and might rarely seen even for the god's champion that he is, earning himself the name of 'Hero-Knight of Waterdeep.'~
@769  = ~This... this is ridiculous. I do not even know what I find more appalling, the insinuation that mortals worship me, or naming me my god's champion. <CHARNAME>, let us go, before I start to consider this a blasphemy.~
@770  = ~We should not let ourselves be drawn into this dispute, <CHARNAME>. It's not ours.~
@771  = ~Such insufferableness. This young lady is in need of our help, <CHARNAME>!~
@772  = ~No! I cannot let you murder these innocents, <CHARNAME>!~
@773  = ~How easily these braggarts are scared away. Well done, <CHARNAME>.~
@774  = ~This is not our fight, <CHARNAME>. We should not take sides.~
@775  = ~All this need and sorrow all around us... <CHARNAME>, let us strive with urgency to find a way to save this city from its attackers.~
@776  = ~With due respect of your anger, sir, <CHARNAME> is the wrong one upon which to vent your wrath!~
@777  = ~I cannot bear this traitor's speech! We will not listen to any of his words. <CHARNAME>, be warned, as I will not tolerate either of the conditions he is demanding! There has to be a righteous way to end this! ...Without threatening the young man's life, if possible.~
@778  = ~No! I cannot let you murder this innocent woman, <CHARNAME>!~
@779  = ~No! I cannot let you murder this mage, <CHARNAME>!~
@780  = ~Why do you mock a helpless man behind bars?~
@781  = ~I believe this man to speak the truth. We should go and talk to the Countess. This should not delay us too much.~
@782  = ~I believe this man to speak the truth. We could go and talk to the Countess. This should not delay us too much.~
@783  = ~Could this be true? Evil shows itself in so many ways.~
@784  = ~Do not pester this lady! She has no use for the likes of you.~
@785  = ~Love! Remember what was told to us. Do not put yourself into such danger!~
@786  = ~Lady <CHARNAME>, I doubt we have time for this!~
@787  = ~Lady <CHARNAME>! Remember what was told to us. We cannot follow you where this creature will take you!~
@788  = ~Love...~
@789  = ~Ah! This is only for the paying lady, I am afraid. Come this way...~
@790  = ~<CHARNAME>! Remember what was told to us. We cannot follow you where this creature will take you!~
@791  = ~<CHARNAME>! Why do you neglect your duties for this?!~
@792  = ~Oh, but the duties will be so much lighter, afterwards! (giggle)~
@793  = ~What a wonderful outcome! <CHARNAME>, I thank you for this idea. Let us go and deliver this joyous piece of news to the elves!~
@794  = ~What? No! Man, you should be warned... by Helm, too late. <CHARNAME>! This man might be dishonorable, but now we will have to answer for his death. This is unbearable!~
@795  = ~Tahaha! Er, wha...~
@796  = ~It was a good deed, warning him. He might be a thief, but our honor does not allow otherwise.~
@797  = ~I... surely hope his teleportation will not be hindered by Yaga Shura's barrier! <CHARNAME>, let us double our efforts to save this city, and all in it!~
@798  = ~By Helm... This man needs more than mere healing, <CHARNAME>. But it would still be possible to raise him, if we can afford the magic.~
@799  = ~She might have aimed at the right thing, but her deeds were against the law. The current law, at least. But... a death sentence?...~
@800  = ~Honor forbids us to buy any of these stolen goods, <CHARNAME>! What do you want me to do, look in the other direction?!~
@801  = ~What? What madness is this? Can you not see that <CHARNAME>...~
@802  = ~Silence! There is nothing to be said.~
@803  = ~A lich threatening your young daughter! <CHARNAME>, it is good we came here in time. This evil must be stopped!~
@804  = ~Your cowardice started the moment you promised your soul in exchange for a better life! Now you let your wife and daughter suffer because of it! Come to your senses, before you lose the last piece of your integrity!~
@805  = ~Your cowardice started the moment you promised your soul in exchange for a better life! You tricked others into doing the dangerous work for you, you let your wife and daughter die in your stead. All integrity in you is lost. Your remorse has no meaning!~
@806  = ~I have the strong impression this... man will not give in unless we do as he said, <CHARNAME>!~
@807  = ~Love! I cannot let you... (takes a deep breath) I trust you, <CHARNAME>.~
@808  = ~No, Balthazar! You do not know what destiny lays in <CHARNAME>'s hands. No one does, not even the gods!~
@809  = ~By Helm... This is the moment. Do not look at me, love. Make your own decision, and make it independent of anything that happened in the past. This... this is greater than any vow of marriage you made. Where you are invited to go, mortals and their words mean little. Know that I will accept your choice, regardless.~
@810  = ~By Helm, so it was all true. Alaundo's prophecies, coming true in this moment.~
@811  = ~It is a great chance you have, <CHARNAME>. But remember, the powers you are offered are from an evil source! Do not choose godhood if you are not willing to fight an endless struggle against the evil taint of your heritage.~
@812  = ~I... I love you. I will not stop doing so, ever.~
@813  = ~Love! You... you stay? I am speechless and humbled. Never would I have dreamed this possible! You know I did not believe this ending could ever be! You showed me, once again.~
@814  = ~Does... does this mean you will stay with me? That it has come to an end? The Bhaal essence, the evil powers, the nightmares... Being hunted by evil forces... Forgive me, I have to regain my countenance... (clears his throat, his eyes beaming) By Helm!~
@815  = ~Love... So I have to let you go. But I do not lose you, love. I gain you - you will have the status you always had in my heart, <CHARNAME>: a goddess!~
@816  = ~I will be proud to see you rise, knowing you were the woman who loved me. By Helm... Words are meaningless. I love you, <CHARNAME>. May this godly power be your tool of righteousness! That I wish from the bottom of my heart.~
@817  = ~<CHARNAME>, I followed you, and we achieved a lot of good. I will not support an evil Bhaal-child's fights.~ [c#ablank]
@818  = ~Alaundo's prophecies come true, and a war shakes the lands. I will return to the Order, where I am needed. Next time we meet, we might be on different sides, if we ever meet again at all.~
@819  = ~(sigh)~
@820  = ~What a choice, <CHARNAME>. But remember, the powers you are offered are from an evil source! You already lost the fight against the evil taint of your heritage... Do not choose godhood if you want to remain true to yourself!~
@821  = ~Love... So I have to let you go. You... you will now rise to what you always were in my heart, <CHARNAME>: a goddess!~
@822  = ~But... but the taint is there to see. I will not be proud to see you rise. By Helm... Words are meaningless. I love you, <CHARNAME>. I love you, and my heart is broken.~
@823  = ~So, you will rise, a newly awakened, evil god... And I was there, helping you to godhood. Helm, forgive me - <CHARNAME>, forgive me!~
@824  = ~I will be nervous, seeing you rise. Be strong, <CHARNAME>! Be strong and resist the evil taint. I will never forget you were the woman who loved me. By Helm... Words are meaningless. I love you, <CHARNAME>. May this godly power be your tool of righteousness! That I wish from the bottom of my heart.~
@825  = ~<CHARNAME>, I have to warn you... I see a tendency to evil in your behaviour.~ [c#ablank]
@826  = ~It is not... plain to see. But you seem to be... eager to retrieve your godly father's throne, yet decline to learn about what the solar is trying to teach you about your past, about yourself...~
@827  = ~Be careful, love! It scares me to see you so. A lot!~
@828  = ~Be careful, <CHARNAME>!~
@829  = ~Do not give in to aggression and blood hunger - not now, after all you have done to withstand it. This is the silent path of corruption, and a dangerous one it is.~
@830  = ~<CHARNAME>, there is a clear tendency in your behavior, and I am not happy with it. Not at all!~ [c#ablank]
@831  = ~After all you have done to prevent it... After all you gave to fight the evil taint of your father's godly powers, I see you slip silently to the dark side, showing the hunger for your father's throne. What is happening?~
@832  = ~I see you turning to the dark side of your divine blood, giving in to the hunger for Bhaal's throne.~
@833  = ~This is difficult for me, very difficult. I know you are the one to stop the prophecy - there is a great evil out there, a threat to the world as we know it. And it is you who are destined to stop it.~
@834  = ~So, I will fight on your side, <CHARNAME>, my love - if you want me to. But my heart is heavy. Do not let us waste time with idle talking. We have a great task to accomplish.~ 
@835  = ~So, I will fight on your side, <CHARNAME> - if you want me to. But my heart is heavy. Do not let us waste time with idle talking. We have a great task to accomplish.~
@836  = ~But there is a greater evil here, and we can leave him neither the realm of your godly father, nor Bhaal's essence. I will aid you in your battle for your soul - and watch your... development closely. By Helm!~
@837  = ~Do not let yourself be overwhelmed by the dark side, <CHARNAME>! Be strong! We are fighting for your soul, do not loose your strength in this struggle just yet!~
@838  = ~I... I know I swore differently, once. But I cannot be witness to you walking the lands, being evil... I will try to seek oblivion in the Order's fighting missions... Forgive me.~
@839  = ~By Helm... This is the moment. Do not look at me, love. Make your own decision, and make it independent of anything that happened in the past. This... this is greater than any promise of marriage you gave. Where you are invited to go, mortals and their words mean little. Know that I will accept your choice, regardless.~
@840  = ~I'll defend myself!~

/* addition to c#ajanj_pr.d */


@841  = ~What?! You... you would have *known* about <CHARNAME>'s capture?!~
@842  = ~This... this is hard to bear. Let us move on, <CHARNAME>, before I forget that I am following your orders and start clearing this place!~
@843  = ~Treason?! You little fool, better not cross our path again!~
@844  = ~Oh, but that would mean you'd be still alive, which would be a good thing, yes? As I said, I am awfully sorry for my rudeness.~
@845  = ~You! You dare talk words like these?! We should strike you down where you stand!~
@846  = ~Ah, but haven't you got worse problems to face right now, and are in desperate need of help? Watch where you point that sword now, will you? And let me talk to to <CHARNAME>.~
@847  = ~We know as much already, traitor! Do not think you can undo what you did with your lame attempts of pretending to be helpful to us!~
@848  = ~Is this what we do now, stealing ships? I might agree to use a pirate's ship for our own purpose, <CHARNAME>, but why are you trusting this man, who betrayed and lied to us already?~

@849  = ~Greetings to you, Sir Ajantis! We are all very happy to have you back.~ [c#ablank]
@850  = ~I thank you, Lady Tirlana. I owe my freedom to <CHARNAME>.~

/* new for v20 */
@851   = ~Ajantis, I am not keen on this myself, but we need Mae'Var's trust to procure the proof of his treachery. I want to use every opportunity to raise the gold we need to get to Irenicus.~
@852   = ~Ajantis, Mae'Var holds Husam captive. I will play along until I can free him.~ 
@853  = ~I do not feel good about having to work for the Shadow Thieves... but I will help you as long as I can fulfill the tasks with a clear conscience.~
@854  = ~Well, it seems you are decided to take this path. But you may rest assured that I won't hesitate to let the light of righteousness shine, should it be necessary.~
